<font color="#FF0000">DIALOGS SUCH AS THESE</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 28  0:48:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I fully agree on the wasted talent of those who were lost in war.  This is one of those trade-offs that we'll never be able to know.  I do know that some of those loved ones, ones who have communicated with me, would give anything to have those loved ones back.  To them, those directly affected, this sacrifice was the waste of good men (and women).  <br><br>
I know that I gave my own parents a lot of heartburn and stress by going over to Vietnam.  I also know that if I would not have come back the way I did, that several other lives would be much different.  <br><br>
This tragedy has affected everyone in America, and much beyond.  The Vietnamese lost, the Cambodians, Laotions, Australians, Koreans and Canadians all have lost much in the way of &quot;human resources.&quot;  <br><br>
Perhaps, when all is said and done (if that ever happens), these conversations will also provide insight into ways of constructively heading off wars of this type.  Then, when we remember those fallen friends, and the contribution that they could have made (maybe someone would already have conquered AIDS by now if not for this war), perhaps we can pause, think about what our and their motivations are in a current conflict, and appreciate the complexity of interacting cultures.  <br><br>
Then the full contributions of these insights through dialog will have become manifest.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


